attributes.magic: ELF 64-bit LSB executable, x86-64, version 1 (SYSV), statically linked, with debug_info, not stripped

threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

crowdsourced_yara_results.description: This signature detects the presence of a number of Windows API functionality often seen within embedded executables. When this signature alerts on an executable, it is not an indication of malicious behavior. However, if seen firing in other file types, deeper investigation may be warranted.
crowdsourced_yara_results.author: InQuest Labs

crowdsourced_ids_results.rule_raw: alert ( gid:116; sid:58; rev:2; msg:"(tcp) experimental TCP options found"; metadata: policy max-detect-ips drop, rule-type decode; classtype:protocol-command-decode;)

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This ELF binary is a sophisticated, multi-functional Remote Access Trojan (RAT) or C2 beacon, likely part of an advanced persistent threat (APT) toolkit. It features a modular architecture with specialized components for command and control (C2), data exfiltration, lateral movement, and extensive anti-forensic stealth. Key malicious behaviors include process masquerading (renaming itself to kernel worker threads like '[kworker/u16:0]'), interaction with Linux Kernel Modules (LKM) and LD_PRELOAD mechanisms to hide its presence, and automated harvesting of high-value credentials such as SSH keys, AWS tokens, and Kubernetes configurations. The sample also includes integrated network scanning capabilities and the ability to move laterally across compromised environments via SSH and Kubernetes API exploitation. Communication with the C2 is performed over encrypted HTTP channels with specific beaconing and task-polling endpoints.
